##   - ignored (2)
##   - re-scaling to [0, 1] (2)
#For predicting we can use income and balance.
Default_normalized <-predict(norm_model,Default)
Default_normalized=Default_normalized[,-2]

#Using 80% of data for training and remaining 20% for testing.
Index_Train <-createDataPartition(Default_normalized$default,p=0.8,list=FALSE)
Train<-Default_normalized[Index_Train,]
Test<-Default_normalized[-Index_Train,]

#default status is the first column for class output
# 2nd and 3rd column for normalized "balance and "income"
Train_Predictors<-Train[,2:3]
Test_Predictors<-Test[,2:3]

Train_labels<-Train[,1]
Test_labels<-Test[,1]

#training a knn model where k=4
Predicted_Test_labels <-knn(Train_Predictors,Test_Predictors,cl=Train_labels,k=4)
head(Predicted_Test_labels)
## [1] No No No No No No
## Levels: No Yes

Confusion Matrix: It can be used for performance measurement for machine learning classification problem

where output can be two or more classes.It is a table with 4 different combinations of predicted and actual values.

Here the target class will be positive and negative. It has four categories::1)TRUE Positive(TP) 2)TRUE negative(TN) 3)FALSE Positive(FP) 4)FALSE Negative(FN).

install.packages("caret")
## Warning: package 'caret' is in use and will not be installed
confusion <- confusionMatrix(data=Predicted_Test_labels,
                             reference=Test_labels)
print(confusion)

AN ROC Curve is a receiver Operating characteristic curve is a graph showing the performance of classification model at all classification Thresholds.

It has two parameters True Positive Rates and False Positive Rates.

if(!require(pROC)) install.packages("pROC")
## Loading required package: pROC
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
data(Default_normalized)
## Warning in data(Default_normalized): data set 'Default_normalized' not found
if(!require(DT)) install.packages(DT)
## Loading required package: DT
DT::datatable(Default_normalized)
rocobj <- plot.roc(as.numeric(Default_normalized$default),as.numeric(Default_normalized$balance),
                   
                   main = "Confidence intervals of sensitivity/Specificity", 
                   percent=TRUE,
                   ci = TRUE,                  # compute AUC (of AUC by default)
                   print.auc = TRUE)           # print the AUC (will contain the CI)
## Setting levels: control = 1, case = 2
## Setting direction: controls < cases
ciobj <- ci.se(rocobj,                         # CI of sensitivity
               specificities = seq(0, 100, 5)) # over a select set of specificities
plot(ciobj, type = "shape", col = "#1c61b6AA")     # plot as a blue shape
plot(ci(rocobj, of = "thresholds", thresholds = "best")) # add one threshold
